Fix browserify support for loose and walkWe need the `require` call to be ignored in the first pass, which isnwhy it was inserted as `_dereq_` in the first place.  This is needed inncase the user is loading acorn and acorn_loose/acorn_walk as separatenscript tags.nnHowever, if the file is loaded via browserify (i.e. a second browserifynpass) we need that require to be processed, which wasn't working beforenbecause it had been renamed to `_dereq_`.nnThis is fixed by using a placeholder, which gets swapped out after thenfirst browserify pass has completed.n

[loose parser] Fix interpretation of `f.`Before this the ast produced by parse_dammit crashed in the followingncode, as Uglify correctly noticed that f. is invalid.nnsample = 'f.';nnloose = require('acorn/acorn_loose');nuglify = require('uglify-js');nnout = new uglify.OutputStream();nast = loose.parse_dammit(sample);nast = uglify.AST_Node.from_mozilla_ast(ast);nast.print(out);n// TypeError: Cannot call method 'toString' of undefinedn// member_exp.computed = false && member_exp.property == nnconsole.log(out.toString());nnAfter this the round-tripped AST looks like: `t.u00e2u009cu0096;;`, which isnconsistent with how `foo.{` is parsed.nnI also considered making it parse as t[], but as this only turns up innthe wild when people try to use multiline strings, I felt it was betternto be obviously wrong.n
